## Overview
AWS Organizations is a service that helps you centrally manage and govern multiple AWS accounts from a single management account.

---

## Why Use AWS Organizations?

- Centralized account management
- Consolidated billing
- Volume discounts
- Centralized security policies
- Centralized access control
- Simplified compliance and governance

---

## Core Components

### Management Account
- The primary AWS account
- Creates and manages the organization
- Pays the consolidated bill

### Member Accounts
- Individual AWS accounts
- Belong to the organization
- Can be grouped into Organizational Units (OUs)

### Organizational Units (OUs)
- Logical groups of AWS accounts
- Apply policies to multiple accounts

Example:

Company

├── Security OU

├── Development OU

├── Production OU

└── Testing OU

---

## Service Control Policies (SCPs)

SCPs define the maximum permissions available for AWS accounts within an organization.

Example:

Security OU

↓

Deny EC2 Terminate

↓

All accounts inside Security OU cannot terminate EC2 instances.

Important:
- SCPs never grant permissions.
- SCPs only limit permissions.
- IAM policies are still required.

---

## Consolidated Billing

Benefits:

- Single monthly bill
- Shared Reserved Instance discounts
- Shared Savings Plans
- Volume pricing discounts
- Easier cost tracking

Example:

Without Organizations

Account A → Separate Bill

Account B → Separate Bill

Account C → Separate Bill

With Organizations

Management Account

↓

One Combined Bill

---

## Tag Policies

Maintain consistent resource tagging.

Example:

Correct

Environment=Production

Incorrect

env=Prod

Tag policies help standardize tags across accounts.

---

## Backup Policies

Centralized backup management.

Example:

Daily backup

↓

Every account automatically follows the backup policy.

---

## AI Services Opt-Out Policies

Control whether AWS AI services can use customer content for service improvements where applicable.

